+{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01X7HDmPZ9XYrwKCX7SoCxNT","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Good -- all 98 tests pass, the build succeeds, and lint is clean. Now I have a thorough understanding of both the requirements and the implementation. Let me produce the review.\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: In-Memory Task Queue System\n\n## Overall Assessment\n\nThe implementation is well-structured, clean, and delivers on all 12 phases. All 98 tests pass, TypeScript compiles cleanly, and lint reports no issues. The code is readable and the single-class design keeps things easy to follow. That said, there are several correctness bugs, missing requirement implementations, and edge cases worth addressing. I have organized the findings by severity.\n\n---\n\n## CRITICAL Issues (Must Fix)\n\n### 1. Missing Circular Dependency Detection (Phase 7)\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, `add()` method (lines 47-53)\n\n**Requirement from `/workspace/phases/phase-07.md`:**\n> \"Circular dependencies (direct or indirect) must be detected and rejected at task-creation time.\"\n\nThe implementation validates that dependency task IDs exist, but performs no circular dependency check whatsoever. If task A depends on task B, and then task B (while pending) has a new task C added that depends on A, there is no detection of the cycle. More critically, a task could even be added with a dependency on itself if the add method somehow allowed it (though self-referencing is prevented by the fact that the task does not exist yet at validation time).\n\nConsider a scenario like this:\n\n```typescript\nconst a = q.add('a');\nconst b = q.add('b', { dependencies: [a.id] });\n// Now if someone tries to make a depend on b after the fact, the current\n// API doesn't allow it. But indirect cycles through completed-state\n// manipulation could still occur.\n```\n\nWhile the current API makes it hard to create cycles (since a task must already exist to be referenced as a dependency), the specification explicitly requires cycle detection. A graph traversal (DFS/BFS) should be performed at add-time to walk the transitive dependency chain and confirm no path leads back to the task being added.\n\nThe test suite in `/workspace/tests/phase07-dependencies.test.ts` also lacks a test for circular dependency detection, which means the requirement is entirely unaddressed.\n\n### 2. Middleware `nextCalled` Tracking Produces Incorrect Behavior for Post-Next Middleware Logic\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, lines 433-451\n\n```typescript\nprivate async runMiddlewareChain(\n  task: Task,\n  middlewares: MiddlewareFn[],\n  index: number,\n  handler?: HandlerFn\n): Promise<void> {\n  if (index < middlewares.length) {\n    let nextCalled = false;\n    await middlewares[index](task, async () => {\n      nextCalled = true;\n      await this.runMiddlewareChain(task, middlewares, index + 1, handler);\n    });\n    if (!nextCalled) {\n      return;          // <--- This is dead code in the non-next case\n    }\n  } else if (handler) {\n    await handler(task);\n  }\n}\n```\n\nThe `nextCalled` check on line 445 is functionally dead code. When a middleware does NOT call `next()`, the `await middlewares[index](...)` call completes, `nextCalled` is `false`, and then `return` executes -- but the function would have returned anyway since there is no code after the `if (!nextCalled)` block. The check does nothing.\n\nThe real issue is behavioral: the `process()` method at line 421 auto-completes a task if its status is still `'processing'` after the middleware chain returns:\n\n```typescript\nawait this.runMiddlewareChain(task, middlewares, 0, handler);\nif (task.status === 'processing') {\n  this.complete(task.id);\n}\n```\n\nThis means when a middleware deliberately skips `next()` (e.g., to filter/reject a task), the task is still auto-completed. This contradicts the Phase 11 requirement:\n\n> \"If a middleware does NOT call 'next', the task processing is skipped.\"\n\nIf processing is \"skipped,\" it is unclear whether the task should be completed or left in processing state. The current behavior (auto-completing) means a middleware that intentionally blocks a task from being processed still results in a `completed` status. The test on line 48 of `/workspace/tests/phase11-middleware.test.ts` validates that the handler is not called, but does not assert the final task status, so this ambiguity goes untested.\n\nA middleware that skips `next()` likely intends for the task to NOT be marked completed. The task should either remain in `processing` for manual handling, or be explicitly failed/cancelled by the middleware. At minimum, when `next()` is not called, the task should not be auto-completed.\n\n---\n\n## IMPORTANT Issues (Should Fix)\n\n### 3. `maxRetries: 0` Results in Immediate Failure Without Any Processing Attempt\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, `fail()` method (lines 172-192)\n\nThe retry logic is:\n\n```typescript\nif (task.attempt < task.maxRetries) {\n  // Re-queue with backoff delay\n  ...\n} else {\n  // Exhausted retries — move to DLQ\n  task.status = 'failed';\n  this.addToDeadLetterQueue(task, error);\n}\n```\n\nWhen `maxRetries` is 0, after the first attempt (attempt=1), `1 < 0` is false, so the task goes straight to the DLQ. This behavior technically works -- \"0 retries means 0 additional attempts\" -- and the tests confirm this is the intended behavior. However, this is semantically confusing because `maxRetries` actually means \"maximum total attempts\" rather than \"maximum number of re-tries.\" With `maxRetries: 1`, the task gets 1 attempt and 0 retries, not 1 retry. This is inconsistent with the property name but is consistent with how the tests use it, so it is arguably intentional. Worth documenting clearly.\n\n### 4. Sorting Tiebreaker for Delayed Tasks Does Not Match Phase 4 Specification\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, `next()` method, lines 122-128\n\n**Requirement from `/workspace/phases/phase-04.md`:**\n> \"When multiple delayed tasks become available simultaneously, they should be ordered by availability time, then priority, then FIFO.\"\n\nThe implementation sorts by:\n1. Priority (ascending)\n2. AvailableAt (ascending)\n3. CreatedAt (ascending, as FIFO proxy)\n\nThe specification says the order should be: `availableAt, then priority, then FIFO`. These are different orderings. The current implementation prioritizes priority over availability time, while the spec says availability time should come first. However, the Phase 3 specification says:\n\n> \"When retrieving the next task, higher-priority tasks (lower number) are returned first.\"\n\nThese two requirements conflict. The current implementation (priority-first) is arguably more useful and passes all tests, but it does deviate from the Phase 4 specification's stated ordering. This should be acknowledged and either the code or the specification should be updated for consistency.\n\n### 5. `redriveTask` Does Not Reset `maxRetries`\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, `redriveTask()` method, lines 215-231\n\nWhen redriving a task, the method resets `attempt`, `progress`, `error`, `status`, and `availableAt`, but does not reset `maxRetries`. The Phase 6 requirement says:\n\n> \"It should be possible to move a dead-lettered task back to its original queue for a fresh round of retries.\"\n\nThe task's `maxRetries` was set at creation time and is not changed. This is fine if the original `maxRetries` was adequate. However, consider that a cancelled task has `maxRetries` set to 0 (by the `cancel()` method at line 345). If somehow a cancelled task ended up in the DLQ (which currently cannot happen since cancel does not move to DLQ), it would be redriven with `maxRetries: 0` and fail immediately again.\n\nMore practically, the fact that `cancel()` mutates `maxRetries` is a side effect that could leak into other logic paths. The `cancel()` method at line 345:\n\n```typescript\ncancel(taskId: string): boolean {\n  ...\n  task.status = 'cancelled';\n  task.maxRetries = 0;  // Why is this needed?\n  return true;\n}\n```\n\nSetting `maxRetries = 0` is unnecessary since the task's status is already `cancelled`, and `fail()` checks `task.status !== 'processing'` before doing anything. A cancelled task cannot re-enter the fail/retry path because `next()` only returns `pending` tasks.\n\n### 6. Shutdown Polling Mechanism Uses Busy-Wait with `setTimeout`\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, `doShutdown()` method, lines 490-501\n\n```typescript\nawait new Promise<void>((resolve) => {\n  const check = () => {\n    const stillProcessing = processingTasks.filter((t) => t.status === 'processing');\n    if (stillProcessing.length === 0 || Date.now() >= deadline) {\n      resolve();\n      return;\n    }\n    setTimeout(check, 10);\n  };\n  check();\n});\n```\n\nThis polling loop has several issues:\n\n- **The `processingTasks` array is captured at the start of `doShutdown`**. Any tasks that transition from `pending` to `processing` between the snapshot and the polling loop would be missed. While `shutdownState.initiated` prevents new tasks from being added, existing pending tasks could still be picked up by a `next()` call made after the snapshot is taken.\n\n- **The 10ms polling interval is a busy-wait pattern.** For a library, this is wasteful. An event-driven approach (e.g., having `complete()` and `fail()` emit events) would be more efficient. For an in-memory queue this is acceptable but not ideal.\n\n- **No cleanup of the `setTimeout` on resolution.** When the deadline is reached and tasks are force-cancelled, any pending `setTimeout` could still fire after the promise resolves. This is benign (the function will immediately return since `resolve()` was already called) but is not clean.\n\n### 7. `clearDeadLetterQueue` Deletes Tasks from the Main Task Map\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, lines 233-242\n\n```typescript\nclearDeadLetterQueue(queueName?: string): void {\n  const queue = queueName ?? DEFAULT_QUEUE;\n  const dlq = this.deadLetterQueues.get(queue);\n  if (dlq) {\n    for (const entry of dlq) {\n      this.tasks.delete(entry.task.id);\n    }\n    this.deadLetterQueues.set(queue, []);\n  }\n}\n```\n\nThis deletes tasks from `this.tasks`, which means `q.get(taskId)` will return `null` for a task that was cleared from the DLQ. This might be intentional for garbage collection, but it is undocumented behavior. If any dependent task references a cleared DLQ task's ID, `getDependencyStatus()` would still list it in the `pending` array but `get()` would return `null`. The `resolveDependents()` method iterates `this.tasks.values()`, so cleared DLQ tasks would no longer be found by any lookup -- but their IDs would still exist in other tasks' `dependencies` arrays, creating phantom dependencies that can never be resolved.\n\n### 8. Progress Listeners Are Not Cleaned Up on Task Completion/Failure/Cancellation\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`\n\nWhen a task completes, fails, or is cancelled, any registered progress listeners remain in `this.progressListeners`. These listeners will never fire again (since `reportProgress` checks for `processing` status) but they represent a memory leak for long-lived `TaskQueue` instances that process many tasks. The `onProgress` method (line 318) stores listeners indefinitely unless manually unsubscribed.\n\n---\n\n## Suggestions (Nice to Have)\n\n### 9. `getQueues()` Returns Queues for All Task Statuses Including Failed/Cancelled/Completed\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, lines 149-155\n\nThe method iterates all tasks and collects queue names. This includes queues that only have completed or failed tasks and no pending work. Depending on use case, this could be misleading. Consider whether the method should filter to only \"active\" queues, or document that it returns all queues that have ever had tasks.\n\n### 10. Cron Parser Is Very Limited and Rejects Valid Common Patterns\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/cron.ts`\n\nThe cron parser only supports three patterns: `*/N * * * *`, `0 * * * *`, and `0 0 * * *`. The Phase 10 spec explicitly limits scope to these three, so this is fine for requirements compliance. However, `parseCron` would reject `5 * * * *` (every hour at minute 5) which uses the exact same cron format. If the system is ever extended, the parser will need significant rework. This is acceptable for now given the spec.\n\n### 11. No Validation for Negative or Non-Numeric `delay` Values\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, `add()` method, line 60\n\n```typescript\n} else if (options.delay && options.delay > 0) {\n```\n\nThe `> 0` check means negative delays are silently ignored (treated as no delay). It would be better to explicitly throw on negative values to catch caller mistakes early. A `delay` of `NaN` would also be silently ignored due to how JS comparisons work with `NaN`.\n\n### 12. `size()` Only Counts Pending Tasks\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, lines 136-145\n\nThe `size()` method only counts `pending` tasks. There is no method to get total task count (including processing, completed, failed, cancelled). This is technically fine per the Phase 1 spec (\"how many tasks are waiting\") but could be useful for monitoring.\n\n### 13. Type Safety: `Task<T>` Generic is Erased When Stored\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, line 88\n\n```typescript\nthis.tasks.set(task.id, task as Task);\n```\n\nThe generic `T` is erased when the task is stored in the map (which is typed as `Map<string, Task>`). The `get()` method returns `Task | null` without the generic, so callers lose type information about the payload. This is a common limitation with heterogeneous collections and is acceptable, but worth noting.\n\n### 14. `fail()` Method Optional Error Parameter Creates Inconsistent DLQ Entries\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, line 172\n\n```typescript\nfail(taskId: string, error?: string): void {\n```\n\nWhen `fail()` is called without an error message, the DLQ entry will have `lastError: undefined`. This is fine structurally but means consumers of the DLQ need to handle the case where `lastError` is missing, even though a task presumably failed for a reason.\n\n---\n\n## What Was Done Well\n\n- **Clean, readable code structure.** The single-class design with clearly commented phase sections makes the code easy to navigate and understand.\n- **Good defensive programming.** Input validation on priority ranges, task status checks before state transitions, and null-safe returns are consistently applied.\n- **Correct exponential backoff implementation.** The formula `backoffDelay * 2^(attempt-1)` is correctly applied.\n- **Proper idempotent shutdown.** The `shutdown()` method correctly caches and returns the same promise on repeated calls.\n- **Immutable returns where appropriate.** `getDeadLetterQueue()` returns a shallow copy, preventing callers from mutating internal state.\n- **Clean TypeScript usage.** The types are well-defined, exports are clean, and the code compiles under strict mode.\n- **Solid test coverage.** 98 tests across all 12 phases cover the core behaviors thoroughly.\n\n---\n\n## Summary of Required Actions\n\n| Priority | Issue | Location |\n|----------|-------|----------|\n| Critical | Missing circular dependency detection | `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts` `add()` |\n| Critical | Middleware skip does not prevent auto-completion | `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts` `process()` + `runMiddlewareChain()` |\n| Important | Sort order contradicts Phase 4 spec (priority vs availableAt first) | `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts` `next()` lines 122-128 |\n| Important | `redriveTask` does not reset `maxRetries`; `cancel` unnecessarily mutates it | `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts` lines 215-231, 338-346 |\n| Important | Shutdown snapshot misses tasks that become processing after snapshot | `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts` `doShutdown()` lines 483-501 |\n| Important | `clearDeadLetterQueue` creates phantom unresolvable dependencies | `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts` lines 233-242 |\n| Important | Progress listeners leak memory on task completion | `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts` |"},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a40c909 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 49077\ntool_uses: 39\nduration_ms: 129461</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"bbf996d8-eb78-4498-a67c-80ac6eebe0fd","uuid":"e254cadb-6080-4da9-a8ef-10e350f3b569","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Review the implementation of the in-memory task queue system for correctness, edge cases, and code quality. The implementation is across these files:\n- src/types.ts - Type definitions\n- src/cron.ts - Cron expression parsing\n- src/TaskQueue.ts - Main TaskQueue class\n- src/index.ts - Exports\n\nThe system implements 12 phases:\n1. Basic FIFO queue\n2. Named queues\n3. Priority ordering\n4. Delayed/scheduled tasks\n5. Retry with exponential backoff\n6. Dead letter queue\n7. Task dependencies\n8. Concurrency control\n9. Progress tracking and cancellation\n10. Recurring tasks (cron)\n11. Middleware pipeline\n12. Graceful shutdown\n\nCheck for:\n- Correctness issues\n- Missing edge cases\n- Code quality problems\n- Issues with the middleware pattern (especially the nextCalled tracking)\n- Issues with the shutdown polling mechanism\n- Any issues with the retry/backoff logic\n- Issues with dependency resolution","agentId":"a40c909","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Good -- all 98 tests pass, the build succeeds, and lint is clean. Now I have a thorough understanding of both the requirements and the implementation. Let me produce the review.\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: In-Memory Task Queue System\n\n## Overall Assessment\n\nThe implementation is well-structured, clean, and delivers on all 12 phases. All 98 tests pass, TypeScript compiles cleanly, a